# Evaluative - Challenge Writeup

## Summary
The challenge requires evaluating an 8th-degree polynomial of the form:
P(x) = a₀ + a₁x + a₂x² + ... + a₈x⁸

## Analysis
The primary hurdle is the potential for **Integer Overflow**. 
- The coefficients ($a_i$) and $x$ are between -100 and 100.
- $100^8$ results in $10^{16}$, which exceeds the $2 \times 10^9$ limit of a standard 32-bit signed integer.
- A 64-bit `long long` (which handles up to $9 \times 10^{18}$) is required for accurate computation.

## Solution
We implement an iterative solution in C. We read the 9 coefficients first, then the $x$ value, and calculate the sum using a running power variable to maintain efficiency.

### Source Code (main.c)

#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    long long a[9];
    long long x, result = 0, x_power = 1;

    for (int i = 0; i < 9; i++) {
        if (scanf("%lld", &a[i]) != 1) return 0;
    }
    if (scanf("%lld", &x) != 1) return 0;

    for (int i = 0; i < 9; i++) {
        result += a[i] * x_power;
        x_power *= x;
    }

    printf("HTB{%lld}\n", result);
    return 0;
}
